## Vercel Web Analytics Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the SpinCheck Next.js project.

### Changes Made

**1. Installed @vercel/analytics package**
   - Added `@vercel/analytics` (v2.0.1) to package.json dependencies
   - Generated package-lock.json with all dependency resolutions

**2. Updated app/layout.tsx**
   - Added import: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
   - Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag following Next.js App Router best practices
   - Preserved existing structure and styling

**3. Created .eslintrc.json**
   - Added ESLint configuration to enable linting for the project
   - Used Next.js recommended configuration with TypeScript support

### Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel documentation (https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart), I implemented the Next.js App Router pattern by:
1. Installing the package using npm
2. Importing the Analytics component from `@vercel/analytics/next`
3. Adding the component at the end of the body tag in the root layout

This approach ensures analytics tracking is initialized across all pages in the application.

### Verification

✅ Build completed successfully - no errors
✅ Linting passed - no new errors introduced in modified files
✅ Package.json and package-lock.json properly updated
✅ Code follows existing project conventions and style

### Next Steps

To enable Web Analytics in production:
1. Deploy this code to Vercel
2. Navigate to the project's Analytics section in the Vercel dashboard
3. Click the "Enable" button to activate Web Analytics
4. After deployment, verify analytics are working by checking the browser Network tab for requests to `/_vercel/insights/*`

The Analytics component will automatically handle tracking page views and web vitals once enabled in the Vercel dashboard.
